    "banking_sector": "Iceland's banking sector was completely rebuilt after the 2008 crisis, when the three major banks (Kaupthing, Landsbanki, Glitnir) collapsed. They were reconstituted as Arion Bank, Landsbankinn, and Íslandsbanki. These three now dominate the small market. All three have been partially or fully privatized through IPOs. The sector is well-capitalized but small in absolute terms. Capital controls that were imposed post-crisis have been fully lifted.",
    "digital_banking": "Despite its small size, Iceland has high digital banking adoption. The three banks compete actively on digital features. The small market means banks can move quickly — Iceland often serves as a testing ground for new digital features. Auður (women-focused digital bank) is a notable challenger. Mobile banking apps are well-developed, and the population's digital literacy supports rapid adoption of new features.",
    "consumer_segments": "Icelandic consumers expect full-service digital banking. The small population means banks know their customers well — relationship banking is still important. SMEs are critical, particularly in tourism, fishing, and energy. The wealth management segment is growing as the economy has recovered strongly. Corporate banking is concentrated in a few large sectors.",
