    "demographics": "Sweden has a population of approximately 10.5 million, highly concentrated in urban areas around Stockholm, Gothenburg, and Malmö. The median age is around 41, with a well-educated workforce and one of Europe's highest rates of immigration, making the population increasingly diverse. GDP per capita exceeds $55,000, and household income levels are among the highest globally. The economy is driven by technology, manufacturing (Volvo, Ericsson, IKEA), and financial services. Unemployment is low at around 7%, and the tech sector continues to grow rapidly, with Stockholm being one of Europe's premier startup ecosystems.",
    "banking_sector": "The Swedish banking sector is dominated by four major banking groups: Nordea (pan-Nordic, recently relocated HQ to Helsinki but maintains massive Swedish operations), SEB (strong in corporate and wealth), Handelsbanken (known for decentralized model and UK expansion), and Swedbank (largest retail bank by customer count, strong in Baltics). Together, these four control roughly 75% of Swedish banking assets. Beyond the Big Four, Länsförsäkringar has grown as a bancassurer, Skandiabanken serves a digital niche, and savings banks (Sparbanker) remain locally important. The sector is profitable with strong capital ratios, though net interest margins have been compressed in recent years.",
    "digital_banking": "Sweden is arguably the world's most digitally mature banking market. Swish (P2P payments) has over 8 million users — roughly 80% of the population. BankID is used for virtually all digital identity verification and authentication. Mobile banking app usage exceeds 90% of customers at all major banks.\n\nDespite this, the underlying technology infrastructure at major banks often dates back 20-30 years. Modernization programs are underway: SEB has been investing in cloud migration, Handelsbanken is modernizing its technology stack, and Swedbank has been rebuilding after reputational damage. Klarna, iZettle (now Zettle by PayPal), and Trustly all originated in Sweden, creating a fintech ecosystem that constantly pushes banks to innovate.",
    "consumer_segments": "Retail consumers expect frictionless, mobile-first banking with instant payments and real-time insights. Personal finance management tools are expected, not differentiating. SMEs (which represent 99% of Swedish companies) increasingly demand digital business banking matching consumer quality — digital invoicing, real-time cash flow tools, and instant lending decisions. The corporate segment expects sophisticated treasury management, FX capabilities, and API-based integration with ERP systems. Sweden's wealth management market is substantial, with pension savings culture creating demand for digital investment platforms. Private banking clients expect hybrid models combining digital tools with personal advisory.",
    "spending_trends": "Swedes are heavy digital spenders — e-commerce penetration is among the highest globally. Buy-now-pay-later (pioneered by Klarna) is deeply embedded in consumer behavior. Savings rates are moderate, with a strong culture of pension fund investing. Sustainable/ESG investing has become mainstream — over 60% of new retail investment flows into ESG-aligned funds. Cryptocurrency adoption among younger demographics is above European averages. Housing market dynamics (high property prices, primarily variable-rate mortgages) create significant exposure to interest rate changes.",
